snippet.textDisplay: If you want to reduce waste, the BEST way to do it is to not buy stuff in the first place! Because even if you use up the stuff or give it to someone else, it's eventually going to be used up/expire and probably thrown into a landfill anyway (not to mention the outside packaging of it, the resources used to ship/create it, etc). This is why I'm trying to reduce my collection overall, not buy new stuff, and use up the stuff I have. Eventually I will hopefully have a more minimal routine to replace, in order to create less waste in the long run.

snippet.textDisplay: Foundations are emulsions which means two liquids (example oil and water) dispersed together and stabilized by other ingredients. However, unless there are other changes with the foundation like the color changing, an odd smell or bubbles it's fine to just shake it well and keep using it 👍

snippet.textDisplay: No no no! - Glass containers can be cleaned and go in glass recycling bins and plastic containers can go in plastic recycling bins. Some countries/regions/counties further divide plastic into hard plastic and soft plastic but it should be obvious that almost no makeup packaging is soft plastic. Tin tubes and other metal packagings can go directly in metal recycling bins once possible plastic inserts are removed and electronics must have their batteries taken out if they do come with batteries. Deodorants are also very recyclable. Roll-ons can have the roller balls taken out and donated to charities who sew weighted blankets for kids with autism and deos with aerosols are chemical waste if not empty, while the plastic packaging is plastic recycling if empty.
